The code statements that lead to the bug are:
```java
@Exported
public final List<AbstractProject> getDownstreamProjects() {
    return Jenkins.getInstance().getDependencyGraph().getDownstream(this);
}
```
```java
@Exported
public final List<AbstractProject> getUpstreamProjects() {
    return Jenkins.getInstance().getDependencyGraph().getUpstream(this);
}
```
Reason:
The methods `getDownstreamProjects()` and `getUpstreamProjects()` were annotated with `@Exported`, which allowed them to expose project information without any permission checks. This lack of restrictions meant that users without the necessary permissions could access sensitive information about hidden upstream or downstream projects.

The code statements that fix the bug are:
```java
@Exported(name="downstreamProjects")
@Restricted(DoNotUse.class) // only for exporting
public List<AbstractProject> getDownstreamProjectsForApi() {
    List<AbstractProject> r = new ArrayList<>();
    for (AbstractProject p : getDownstreamProjects()) {
        if (p.hasPermission(Item.READ)) {
            r.add(p);
        }
    }
    return r;
}
```
```java
@Exported(name="upstreamProjects")
@Restricted(DoNotUse.class) // only for exporting
public List<AbstractProject> getUpstreamProjectsForApi() {
    List<AbstractProject> r = new ArrayList<>();
    for (AbstractProject p : getUpstreamProjects()) {
        if (p.hasPermission(Item.READ)) {
            r.add(p);
        }
    }
    return r;
}
```
Reason:
The new methods `getDownstreamProjectsForApi()` and `getUpstreamProjectsForApi()` are introduced with proper permission checks. They only export project information if the user has the `Item.READ` permission for each project, thus preventing unauthorized access to sensitive project relationships. The `@Restricted(DoNotUse.class)` annotation further indicates that these methods should only be used for exporting purposes, enhancing security.

